  "answer": "**Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation*, Volume I (Chapter 21),** argues precisely this.[^1]\n\nComte contends that vices like prostitution produce pleasures for the individual but also natural pains (misery, contempt, disease, etc.) that repress them. Charitable institutions — foundling hospitals (free delivery for unwed mothers), orphanages for illegitimate children, disease hospitals for the afflicted, and asylums for \"repentant\" prostitutes — weaken these repressive pains for the vicious while leaving the pleasures intact, thus encouraging vice.[^2] He illustrates with the career of prostitution, showing how each institution successively eases its burdens (maternity, child-rearing, illness, social exclusion), making \"vice... multiply to infinity.\"[^3]\n\nHe compares these institutions to \"the existence of a society that, out of humanity, made it a duty to go and **break down the doors of prisons**,\" weakening repression of crimes without diminishing their attractions.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [Chapter 21](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [paragraphs](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-33355b-p-682ecc).\n\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-273291).\n\n[^4]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-b31bb4).",
